A Republican strategy to counter the reelection of Obama
Republican leaders justify their policies with the need to combat voter fraud.
However, the Brennan Center dismisses the latter as a myth, affirming that election fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning strikes.
Republican lawyers, by the way, have only registered 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new rules will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures are in part undermining the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the US states are responsible for the conduct of the elections in each state.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of American governments have enacted new laws that make the registration process or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon has gained importance after the November 2010 elections, which saw 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of voting rights in 41 states.
The new election laws require voters to produce photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods for early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on election day, and deny citizens the right to vote for which a court record exists.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to show photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a demand.
The Supreme Court of the United States upheld the constitutionality of Indiana's law in 2008.
Republican authorities were quick to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states that would force voters to show photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal ID card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of US citizens, or 21 million eligible voters, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such ID cards.
However, it is often necessary to pay more than a hundred dollars to obtain the necessary identification.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of those earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65, and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 do not have the required photo identification.
This goes even further.
Students, who are considered voters who increasingly cast their votes for democratic candidates, are not allowed to use their photo ID cards issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs for elections.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic vote.
Because it's obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
In addition, in 2011, Republican lawmakers in eight states promoted legislation that eliminated voter registration on Election Day.
In addition, you have restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the voter registration campaigns in the 2004 general elections helped register some 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the number of new voters registered in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the length of early voting.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of the early voters were African-American, even though they make up only 13% of the state's electorate.
The same is true for the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of the electorate, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites, who represented 76% of the electorate, accounted for only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic lawmakers and their supporters have vigorously opposed the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills were blocked by the vetoes of Democratic governors.
The US Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to limit some of the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the showing of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote.
The democratic critics denounce the party-political nature of the laws passed and see in them a clear goal to influence the results in the states that will determine the outcome of 2012.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that those states that have passed these laws account for 171 of the 270 votes needed in the Electoral College to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these legislative changes on the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new rules will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures undermine in part the democratic system of the United States.
