The Higgs boson is analyzed
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused quite a stir last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence was predicted by the Standard Model - our best or "least-false" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but has not yet been empirically observed.
But physicists are not yet completely sure that it is the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Moreover, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but data are still lacking to be completely certain.
But let's assume that it's the Higgs, because there's a slight risk of being wrong, and let's see what it is.
There is an inescapable law in this world that makes it impossible for two objects to be in the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to break this rule - and don't try too hard, because you will hurt yourself.
Because even if particle physics is a really weird world, it turns out that it also has a law of its own: the Pauli exclusion principle, which says that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they're in the same "quantum state", and that "state" is basically some of their properties.
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, called fermions, who are obedient to the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons, a vicious bunch of anarchists, who have no sanctity -- certainly not this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons, according to the Berkeley Lab's The Particle Adventure website (which is absolutely amazing by the way), fall into two groups: the mesons, which we won't cover here, and the "force particles", through which the great forces of nature propagate, and with which the Higgs boson is somehow related.
But it's important to note that these bosons are not all as exotic creatures as you might think.
If you're able to read this chronicle, it's only because of a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or "light particle", which is the messenger of the electromagnetic force.
When a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" at that exact spot, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" produces an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon, and thus one of the "force carriers" bosons.
Stabilized field
The same is true for the Higgs boson, except that another field, the Higgs field, must be "interrupted" for this boson to show up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the agent must reach very high energies, somewhat like a frozen pond whose surface could only be scratched by a very large rock.
So it takes a giant particle accelerator like CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 kilometers! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don't - for example, a piece of paper would never stick to the refrigerator by itself.
And not all particles interact with the Higgs field equally: those that do have mass, while the others (like the photon, by the way) have no mass.
What good can all this research be for, asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, they are used to verify the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to closely examine any discrepancies between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
There are, by the way, many physicists who are most eager to see such deviations found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter still has major shortcomings, as it does not provide an explanation for gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that makes up about 80% of the matter in the universe (ups again!).
However, no such anomalies have been found at CERN so far.
Effects
The effects of this research on the general population are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there are none.
By the way, back in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser at Bell Labs had no idea that their work would spark such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at the Bell Labs where the laser was invented in the 1960s and who himself developed the first continuous-wave laser in 1962 (the first ones were pulsed) - has already told us that the laser was initially seen as more of a "laboratory prank".
I mean, imagine that.
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments surrounding the research.
For example, in 1969, Willard Boyle, while working in optics, developed a small light sensor.
Although not its original purpose, this sensor now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras worldwide, and it won the Nobel Prize for Physics in 2009.
Of course, this doesn't mean that the LHC's activities will necessarily change our lives, but it does mean that you really can never know...
Palliative care is the best way to die.
Recently, Quebec has discussed the sensitive issue of end-of-life with its Committee on "Dying with Dignity".
Debate must resume shortly, although a bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to look at this in more detail.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. was living alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that had eaten him up had left him with a two-year deadline.
"They gave me five years to live, I've made seven years", he said halfheartedly, lying in his bed in the Victor-Gadbois hospice in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"It's always a shock, though, and you can't be prepared for it", he says.
The disease does its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even from eating himself.
Sitting at a table enjoying a delicious lunch, he resignedly agrees to be helped to eat.
He even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medication, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My biggest wish is that they cure my diarrhea, because this is humiliating", he shared.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man peeing while standing", says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor Gadbois Home.
To return to the childhood phase is an unacceptable humiliation for certain people.
"It depends on the person's ability to take a step back", he says.
Because according to several people who work in palliative care, big events are happening in the midst of these regressions.
The patients who are admitted to the Victor Gadbois Hospice are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage they are no longer showered with so-called "curative" care by the doctors and nurses who care for them.
For Mrs A., 89, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by asphyxiation".
But through the illness, I really got to know my children.
"I have good children", she adds.
"I have no more desires in life", she says before accepting to wear a mask to help her breathe.
She is still expecting a final visit from her son, who is coming from Italy.
The Victor Gadbois Home offers a group of volunteers to provide personal care and assistance with food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed for every 11,700 residents.
That's very little, considering that we're all going to die one day.
Here life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the nurses at the home.
Whether it's physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given a mouthwash of brandy or Pepsi, as desired.
The diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer, who died during the night.
This morning, his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help family members and patients alike", says Nathalie Savard, director of nursing.
At Victor's Home for the Aged, no day is like any other.
Besides a 93-year-old man enjoying the final family gathering in the courtyard, well supported by his pillow as his honor is bowed, a young man of 36 years old, surrounded by his parents, wife, and two small children, dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have been occupied by cancer patients under 45", says Dr. Christiane Martel with concern.
53% of the patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois Home come from their homes, 47% come from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77 percent of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, which is care that is designed to alleviate the suffering of patients when they reach the end of their lives, whether at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor Gadbois Home and the Society for Home Palliative Care in Greater Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this gross inadequacy of Quebec's health care system that is causing several doctors specialising in palliative care to oppose the passage of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been circulated by prominent figures in palliative care, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, expressing their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health care system is not capable of ensuring that everyone has the right to quality palliative care before accepting euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with severe pain and no relief.
I'm afraid the only reason patients want to die is because they're not getting proper health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists are treating their patients with the worst prognoses, and they're stuck until the very last day.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were already minimal when she stopped a painful chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop treatment, she told me that she regretted that I had given up the fight, she said.
But she told me I was finished!
No omnipotent care is needed
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for not granting their wish after their pain has been relieved by a team of palliative care.
But it must be made clear that palliative care is not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Home Palliative Care Society of Greater Montreal, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
Thus, at the end of life, doctors often resort to the terminal sedation, which involves putting the patient to sleep either sporadically or permanently until the time of death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not see this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the option of resorting to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved all say the same phrase, "I want to die".
But that doesn't necessarily mean, "I want you to put me to sleep", but "I want my pain to be alleviated".
