Bitcoin allows you to pay and sell without a bank
The opposite of the current monetary exchange based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between participants.
Moreover, as is so often the case with these technologies, a political vision is at work: the belief that the current monetary system, designed by banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, the Bitcoin invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym) is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros, etc.) and a protocol for secure exchange like BitTorrent, which allows the direct exchange of files.
With 15,000 computers in the network, about 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
Several thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or payment.
After reaching a high of $30 in June 2011, the price of bitcoin fell to $2 five months later before rebounding to around $10 today (the prices are listed on the website bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to the world trade in real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has expressed interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes Bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "in competition with the dollar or euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currency, such as credits, which are used to advance in a video game, which can be earned or bought (and sometimes exchanged) through games.
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
However, the trade is controlled and processed by a central authority each time.
With Bitcoin, all nodes are simultaneously account holders, auditors, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
The difference is that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A set of data associated with this transaction is electronically signed by a double-encryption system.
This allows the network to verify the authenticity of the transaction.
The content of the file also makes it possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the public ledger of accounts distributed throughout the network.
The crucial step is to enter this new transaction in this book.
This is done by a mathematical problem that is run on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of temporary central banker, having the privilege of adding this extra line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and clearer electronic fingerprint.
The computers take the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is hacked.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes can easily check whether it is the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user tries to cheat by paying with the same currency twice in a very short time (less than 10 minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain unlinked, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the problem gets 50 Bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this remuneration will be cut in half periodically, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but it is divisible by one hundred millionth, which leaves some leeway...
In addition, the difficulty of the task increases with each improvement in computing power.
The network has had its ups and downs.
