A Constitution With a Breaking Rod in Egypt
It's a new poker game from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever over the constitutional declaration that temporarily grants him unlimited power, he has decided to put everything on the line.
To everyone's surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the constituent assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
The President-in-Office of the Council has just given this plenary two months to complete its work.
Egypt has now relied for almost two years on a provisional text, amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only served to further divide the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "trample the law".
Its supporters assure that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum was to be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time that forces the brothers to abandon their plan of explaining the text to the Egyptians, paragraph by paragraph.
For the president, it's also a way to regain his public and democratic legitimacy, while the protest rages across the country.
According to confirmations in an interview with the American weekly Time, Mohammed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote in a benevolent manner.
The European Parliament has been asked to vote on the draft constitution, and the Egyptian people have been given an ultimatum: "Either you vote for my draft or I will retain the unlimited power", which should supposedly end after the constitution is adopted.
The text was adopted yesterday in a strange atmosphere by 85 mostly Islamist members of this constituent assembly.
The majority of the Liberals have not responded to the call.
Shortly before the constitutional declaration in mid-November, they turned away, feeling that they had not been able to make their views heard.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities and civil society acted in the same way.
In order to achieve the decision-making capacity, 11 people, deputy members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles were adopted unanimously in most cases.
Commentators found it amusing, by the way, that the only disagreement of the day... was expressed in the time for prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the pendulum of the Constituent Assembly was not exactly on time.
The text, which was adopted last night, contains 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all the attention, remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of the Sharia are the main source of law".
