In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect holy sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the splendor of Bible truths, modern conveniences, and unspoiled nature.
AIF gives you the top five reasons to visit Israel.
Bow before the sacred places
Visit the river Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all those who bathe in this river receive God's blessing.
Galilee is where Jesus performed his miracles, turning water into wine at a wedding feast, walking on water, calming a storm, and catching fish.
It was here that Jesus appeared to his disciples after his resurrection.
However, most of the shrines are in Jerusalem.
Here, believers make the Way of the Cross, or the Via Dolorosa.
The path begins at the Roman fortress of Antonia, the Praetorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the Old City to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on the Mount Golgotha, where the place of the crucifixion, the anointing stone, and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to Christian belief, is the navel of the world, symbolizing the salvation of mankind.
The Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands on the site where, according to Christian legend, the tree from which the cross for the crucifixion of Jesus was made grew.
Jerusalem also contains the holiest place of the Jews - the Western Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 C.E.
Traditionally, people of various faiths leave wishes behind, which are then granted.
Taking a Voyage to the Heights
The ruins of the fortress of Masada are the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in 25 C.E.
They are situated on a rock face in the mountains, some 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
Everyone else is taking a funnel to this historic summit.
In the north of the country, at an altitude of between 5,600 and 6,500 feet [1,600 and 2,040 m], is the famous ski resort of Hermon, which attracts countless tourists during the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain, you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods supposedly lived on the mountain top.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
Not all of them can be visited in one trip.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be visited.
Among them is the Israel Museum, near the Knesset (parliament).
It contains ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in cave systems in the Judean Desert, as well as some 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Tel Aviv Museum of Art is also worth a visit.
It is home to the collection of works by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Akko, you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several rooms of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the visitors and bath attendants of that time.
In Caesarea, you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are generally not accepted.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum, or Yad Vashem, in Tel Aviv, tells one of the most shocking chapters of history.
The most moving section is the Children's Memorial, built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who perished in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When you enter the room, it is pitch black.
The stars are twinkling.
And it's got the names of the Jewish children and the countries where they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
