Israel's three main recreation areas are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red, and the Dead Seas.
Each of the three sites has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums, and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, since the water temperature does not drop below 70 degrees Fahrenheit (21°C) and the air warms to 75 degrees Fahrenheit (23°C).
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and people bathe there year-round.
Incidentally, at 1,400 feet [417 m] below sea level, this unusual sea is the deepest in the world.
Its turquoise-blue water is highly salty, so that even a non-swimmer can easily swim across it.
The surrounding countryside is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural brine) and healing mud, as well as for treating skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, and to calm stressed nerves.
Touching the Secrets of the Ancient World
These secrets are hidden in the old city of Tel Aviv, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia, and Mesopotamia passed through this city.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, it was here that Noah built his ark, and here that Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after the zodiac signs.
Fortuna shall be the legend after all who touch the walls in the alley with their star sign.
In Jaffa, you can meet newlyweds from all over Israel and even other countries at photo sessions.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can wander through the Roman theater and capture the Crusader fortress.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and the residence of Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theater is now used for evening concerts and operas.
List of tourist attractions
If you go to Israel, don't worry about your poor English: about 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
Instead of taking euros, travelers prefer to take dollars, which can easily be exchanged for shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
