According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is observed in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday evening until sundown on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transportation is suspended.
And Sunday morning is the start of the work week.
Many cafes, restaurants, and taverns serve only kosher food, excluding pork, seafood, fish without the skin, and dishes containing both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you can choose from a variety of dishes including mutton and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish hummus pasta, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel), and fruits and vegetables.
