Each year, 13 million foreign workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg, and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to support the families back home.
On December 1, a law came into force requiring every migrant worker to take a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this scheme has only been applied to migrants wishing to work in the service sector, in the municipal housing sector and in retail trade.
However, the tests are to become mandatory for all guest workers in the future, according to the Federal Migration Agency.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals in this area, and it is not the Commission's intention to make any proposals.
Language proficiency must be demonstrated both for obtaining and for renewing a work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is an official language.
