Migrants can take the tests in all cities; more than 160 such centres have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Agency.
But before the law came into force, civil rights activists repeatedly asked the following question in the press: What does it all actually bring?
What changes does the requirement to demonstrate language proficiency bring about for both Russians and foreign workers?
The main thing, according to the spokesman of the Migration Agency, is to reduce the number of forced labourers.
