The problems faced by migrants without jobs, education, language skills and medical examination.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions, who will put him in a dark, cramped barracks under the pretext of help, where he will endure with dozens of his peers for months without food and documents and toil 12 to 14 hours a day.
We get a lot of complaints from our immigrants.
"You are promised this at home, and on arrival you are cheated, your passports are taken away and you don't get the promised salary", said Tolib Shwaripow, head of the main labour migration department of the Tajik Migration Agency.
Don't be like that, boss.
Nevertheless, many citizens of Central Asian republics who want to earn their living in Russia admit that they not only do not know the language of the destination country, but also find it difficult to express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not their fault, but rather the problem: few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford even a decent basic education.
Because their families do not even have the money to feed the children, let alone buy them decent clothes, shoes, and school supplies.
As teenagers, these children then seize the first opportunity to earn money.
"It's difficult without language skills", they admit.
"You feel degraded and inferior".
Civil rights advocates emphasize the following important aspect of the law.
The test is only required for immigrants with legal status.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of the migrant workers remain in Russia illegally.
"Welcome" or "No unauthorized access"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, the language difficulties.
Besides, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and for only one and a half thousand.
