"The brain has so far been little more than a trick"
The popular subject of augmented reality among modern technology lovers is now usually viewed through the lens of special glasses.
First, Google presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, then in November it became known that Microsoft had also applied for a patent.
However, in a conversation with the head of the Interactive 3D Technologies group at Microsoft's Cambridge laboratory, Shahram Izadi, it became clear that the glasses were just a way station for the company's scientists.
It appeals to the possibility of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating virtual open spaces.
- Describe briefly the research activities of your group.
- We are dealing with the interaction between man and machine, but we want to extend the limits of this interaction.
So far, humanity has largely stuck to the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes touched.
But we want to look ahead five to 10 years and see the radical changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and the Kinect sensors are a step up, and nowadays, no Xbox is sold without the Kinect, because everyone is interested in motion control.
- What's the future hold for us?
- Although Kinect has brought interaction to a physical level, much still happens on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) could be improved, the output so far not decisive.
We're trying to change that, working on real three-dimensional rendering systems based on various technologies, including projection.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
This requires that not only the user but also his environment be recognized.
Then we could supplement the real world with virtual objects much more easily.
And first of all, we should get rid of this stupid virtual reality helmet!
- What do you think about voice control?
She's popular, but isn't she overrated?
- It is certainly not the all-purpose solution, since it raises questions of privacy, because one does not always want to inform everyone around one about one's actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each one in its own niche.
For example, in the area of object control in public spaces, we worked on a project where we experimented with short and concise gestures instead of inviting gestures.
The gestures were recorded not by the camera but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It's still relatively large, but theoretically, it could be shrunk to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future is mixed controls, such as gesture and speech.
- What do you mean?
- Would you ask me to hand you this tin can, for example?
You say it and you mean it at the same time.
- I usually just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to tell.
- Does that mean you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and can't do at a given time?
- Not necessarily, but it's about mutual closeness.
I think that in the near future we will have to work on developing new types of sensors that will allow us to detect people's reactions more accurately.
For example, it could be laser sensors, because they have a good resolution at depth, which is very important.
- What are your requirements for modern cameras based on your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors?
Is it lacking resolution, depth, or something else?
- The current generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels at a rate of 1,000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixel itself, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From this point of view, all the current technologies are not good enough for us, because the developers of the algorithms have more work to do.
The resolution along the X- and Y- axis must be taken into account, as well as along the Z-axis.
The speed and number of frames per second are also important.
Human movement is extremely dynamic, and frankly, the current 30 fps is not enough, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor in our lab in Redmond with an adjustable processing delay between 1 and 100 milliseconds, with today's commercial sensors being closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects human-machine interaction.
For my work, I needed a device just like this, but without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently operates with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second one a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually a regular RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the depth of the object.
More cameras could potentially solve the problem...
Or amplify the problem, as more computation would be required.
What would be nice is to have a flexible Kinect-like system where we could play with different camera settings to see how that helps us to get three-dimensional information about a location.
- If I remember correctly, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Don't you think that the best prospect for the application of augmented reality technology in everyday life is the glasses?
Of course, it's not comfortable to always have a smartphone in the palm of your hand on the go, but I think the best option would be a "changing" augmented reality where we could switch from glasses to smartphones via a cloud.
The glasses are a personal gadget, and that's their strength (private is what you can see), but also their weakness, because augmented reality through glasses prevents you from working with others on virtual objects.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is not only accessible to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to ordinary mortals.
There is a problem that critics of this idea often point to: there is no tangible reaction!
The hands feel nothing!
What is your group's response to this objection?
In my lectures, I often talk about augmented reality being the seventh breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the eighth breakthrough could very well be the integration of tactile perception.
One interesting method at the moment is the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection material.
She's a great pressure taker.
But there are also technologies that are actually designed to give the "aerial images" something tangible, for example, the interference of some directional ultrasound beams at a certain point where the finger is located produces a sensation that is, at the moment, as faint as if someone was blowing over the palms.
There are also wrist bands that act on the nerve endings in the fingers, which is also a potential direction.
- Did you try to outsmart the brain?
Make it think it's feeling what it's supposed to feel when it's seeing something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
Here lies another task with which we will have to struggle for a long time to come, namely to make a person who is physically in a closed space believe that he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), moving platforms and large balls.
So far, the brain has been moderately outsmarted, and we have many years of work ahead of us.
And that's what makes working in the field of virtual reality so compelling to a researcher: we're just getting started on a lot of things.
