Šimon Ornest: We want to collect positive energy at our concerts
What do you think about the fact that the end of the world is coming in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster messages that we humans love to jump on.
Our band, the Tap Tap, we make fun of this and say that we are the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you'll also be performing a unique project of three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you explain the project to our readers?
It's a nationwide benefit that we've been planning for two years.
We want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, which is predicted to end on December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
The day before, on 20 December, three concerts will be held simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava, starting at 9 p.m.
The end of the concerts is supposed to be around the time the Mayan calendar ends in the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is 12 hours ahead of us.
Who came up with this idea?
I think it was me who originally came up with the idea, and then we worked on it with our graphic designer Honza Augusta.
We not only want to gather enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think with the public about the state in which we will hand this world over to our children.
To mark the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, T-shirts, bags and key chains against the end of the world, which people can also support us by purchasing them at www.e-tap.cz.
The Tap Tap band also recorded the anti-apocalyptic anthem "World's End" with other artists.
The anthem is already very popular on YouTube, but will it be played at the benefit concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, assuming that everything works out and the end of the world doesn't happen...
The anthem is to be sung by all performers at all three concerts simultaneously.
In addition, the anthems will be broadcast live on Czech television.
The lyrics of the anthem are by Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, also Xindl X sings with...
How did you come to work with both of them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we realize many charity events and concerts...
We are trying to involve these people intensively in our projects.
And it turns out that most of them are interested in working with us, and they enjoy it.
What is the purpose of the proceeds of the anti-doom concerts?
For the creation of the open educational centre Studeo, which we have been working on for six years together with the Tap association at the Jedlička Institute.
The pupils of the Jedlička Institute are regularly supervised by tutors who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the lecturers, we want to help them in this way.
The Jedlička Institute will be completed and will have its own building, which we will then move into with this project.
Each concert features several bands and performers.
What criteria did you use to select these?
We wanted to put together a program that would appeal to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý are performing.
For further information, please refer to the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "big events" planned for the future?
In May we will perform at the Prague Spring for the first time, and for this concert too we are preparing an interesting programme with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are in the USA by then - would also like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans for abroad are not small, you've already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
But The Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it seems at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, meaning that the wheelchairs have to be moved in the luggage compartment, and we have to carry a lot of tool cases and other luggage, of course...
Nevertheless, it has always worked out without problems, ČSA and British Airways have always been very well prepared for us, that I sometimes wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were not long ago, there were no problems.
Through your trips abroad, you have a comparison of what it is like in the different countries with accessibility, how people with disabilities are treated there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything is working better than here, we have just witnessed in Russia that everything in the East is still in its infancy.
In contrast to Prague, Moscow is not handicapped at all, and it is still unusual for a person in a wheelchair to be alone in the city centre.
It is not even a matter of course that a wheelchair user is presented in an elevator, for example.
Fortunately, associations are also being set up to try to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what ways do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are still many things we are lagging behind...
It should be noted, however, that improvement in the situation will always depend on the efforts of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with severe disabilities to be able to move independently in public spaces, to go to museums, to use toilets, etc.
But it is not very common that a larger group of disabled people actively participate in social events, in that we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect for public space and accessibility are one thing, but it's only when we have great athletes, artists, actors, politicians, lawyers in our ranks that things will really start to change.
So far these are only isolated cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap is very popular right now, but if we go back a few years, what was it that motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time I started as a supervisor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in doing something intensive.
And since I am a musician myself and play the saxophone among other things, I have founded a music company with a colleague.
Well, with time, as our host, Láďa Angelovič, used to say, something gets out of control (laughs).
But the band only became known in recent years, or am I mistaken?
It is true that working with well-known singers helped us; we also began actively promoting ourselves.
We have come to realize that if you do something and it's not visible from the outside, your performance is, in a sense, non-existent.
The EU funds also allow us to afford good editors, high-quality equipment and so on.
Was it your goal to get The Tap Tap to this point?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to do things differently.
In show business today, people often copy each other.
This is logical in its own way, since anything new is viewed with caution and accepted only after a long time.
There are few things that are truly unique, and I dare say tap tap is one of them.
The first impression that the viewer usually has is, of course, pity; that's only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned creatures to be pitied.
They are people who can live a full life and develop if they have the means to do so.
I always say that when people with disabilities succeed, it's not just for them, but for the whole of society.
Did your being a strict boss, as many people are told, help you succeed?
To do something well, you must not compromise on many things and you must also be disciplined.
I think that is quite normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and when they find that they have rehearsals twice a week, have to go through preparation phases, and spend a lot of time on concert tours, their enthusiasm quickly fades.
But that's how it works everywhere, in any band that's serious about working and achieving.
The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many of them have been there since the beginning, since 1998?
There is only one, Lada Angelovic.
We're an open group, people come and go, you can't stop that.
Anyone who wants to join is always welcome.
