Last week, at a ministerial meeting of the ESA's member states, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency, becoming the second member country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which joined on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland's journey into space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish space enthusiasts were already interested in space travel, although they did not always find it understandable.
I am reminded, for example, of the lecture given by A. Šternfeld on 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented ideas from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, however, and years later Šternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, which was donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch, for "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomskis' globally recognized contribution to the development of space travel was recognized by, among other things, naming one of the craters on the Earth-facing side of the Moon after him.
Already in 1925, a railway drainage line was built in Poland, for which a rocket engine was planned.
The author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket was to be used to launch or to slow the draisines.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-propelled shells.
The research was carried out by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
The documents submitted show that the research had reached the stage of practical tests.
The research was then interrupted by the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937 the specialist press published the design of a photoelectric fighter rocket by Ing. Rohoziński, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the rocket drive.
Shortly before the war, all projects on the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of activity its work was terminated by the outbreak of war.
Further articles on space travel appeared after the war in the Polish press thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this society is in the November 1954 issue of the magazine Problemy, which has four extensive articles on space travel.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space society.
At that time, the first satellite projects were already in place, and it was clear that space exploration would have a future.
From its very beginning in 1956, the Polish Space Society PTA sought to join the International Space Federation, founded in 1951, and in fact PTA became a full member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became deputy chairman of the International Space Federation.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been heavily involved in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, with the first launch on 10 October 1958.
The rocket, with a maximum flight altitude of 1,800 meters, was about 80 centimeters long and weighed less than 5 kilograms.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 flight testing began in the Błędów Desert with the two-stage RM-2 rocket.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 missile should reach a flight altitude of up to 14,5 km and be used for observing high winds.
However, in 1962 the development was stopped.
The successor of the first RM missile was the Meteor-1 missile, developed in the years 1962 to 1965.
The missile was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of this rocket were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), differing from each other in the size of the transport compartment for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a carrier with a capacity of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight altitude of all three types was 37 km.
In the years 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Institute of Aeronautics, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a take-off weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of approximately 60 km.
After that, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, followed by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites as part of the Interkosmos program, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second Interkosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
