The movie Argo: When the worst comes to the worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of protesting Islamic students occupied the US embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
In exchange for their release, they demanded the extradition of deposed Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the US after the revolution, which had for decades patronized his regime.
There was no positive way out for the American government - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have massively damaged the confidence of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to secure the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a serious blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent failure of the violent attempt to free the hostages only made matters worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days, after negotiations were brokered by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages has sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment at home.
The Iranian debacle was a major contributor to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode in this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy staff managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications at the residence of the Canadian Ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with Canadian authorities, managed to get the refugees out of Iran, using an extravagant story to conceal their true identities - they were travelling with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film crew supposedly visiting the country to shoot a science fiction film.
Combination of the genres
The plan developed by exfiltration expert Tony Mendez also required Hollywood's cooperation.
To give credibility to the cover-up, articles about this film project were published in professional journals, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation were kept secret for a long time, but the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, it is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time it is also a so-called "caper movie", i.e. the story of a successful husaren piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
This changes the mood of the film - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (the title sequence shows iconic contemporary photographs, and there are no major differences in the film version of the same situations).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which are ironic and slightly exaggerated.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the conference table, in the corridors, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable career comeback with this film.
A mocked-up actor has become a respected director, and as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the Krimi Kein Kinderspiel (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller Stadt ohne Gnade (2010).
It's also Affleck's first film not set in the director's native Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that set the previous films of this director apart from the standard Hollywood.
Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film are set in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that actually took place - the opening sequence of the storming of the embassy is very impressive in its clarity, and yet conveys the sense of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team also achieve a similar effect with fictional scenes (the fake film crew at a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
But he works quite successfully with the few, sometimes making a little contribution to reality - which does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the threatening crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a telephone call in America, or the pursuit on the runway, seem a little artificial).
Argo's weakness is its over-scattering, caused by the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are charming in their roles as Hollywood collaborators, but their characters deserve more space, and they are far from alone in this film.
Affleck's film loses some of its appeal, but it is one that can be watched with interest, enjoying its design and its retro style, reminiscent of a thriller from the 1970s.
But he is hard to get excited about.
But it is enough to remind us of a piece of history that is still alive today, and to show how far-fetched the notions of the all-powerful and all-knowing intelligence agencies are.
Guidelines for balloon inflation, bananas and the circus
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually publishes a survey on the most absurd bank charges, decided to hold the contest "The most absurd regulation or idea from the EU workshop" this year.
"This is the idea behind the recent EU plan to introduce a 40% quota for women in the management of large European companies", Patrik Nacher, who is in charge of the organisation of the survey, told the Právo newspaper.
The absurdities mentioned include, for example, the judgment of the European Court of Justice on the unification of insurance rates for men and women.
Until then, women enjoyed an advantage in life insurance because they represented a lower risk to insurance companies.
"More incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be nominated by the end of this year.
The actual vote will then take place by the end of February 2013", Nacher said.
The EU's controversial regulations include the mandatory mixing of bioethanol with fuels, which is harmful to nature, the ban on reliable mercury thermometers simply because they contain a relatively small amount of the dangerous substance, and the directive on the size of chicken cows, which has made eggs much more expensive this year.
The ban on the use of the term 'butter spray' and the ban on the sale of conventional light bulbs have also been criticised in the past.
Bananas must be 14 cm long
The EU apparatus often takes decisions under pressure from one or other business and industrial lobby, whose demands are usually represented in Brussels by one or more member states (the Czech Republic, for example, is currently trying to enforce the demands of Czech banks by using the threat of veto).
Lobby interests also pushed for bananas of the highest commercial grade in the EU to be at least 14 cm long and not to have a 'curvature anomaly'.
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that they merely harmonise the disparate national standards that would impede trade.
The EU has already softened its standards for fruit and vegetables in the face of opposition from some countries, saying that the existing guidelines would lead to food waste.
A possible candidate to win this poll is last year's EU regulation requiring balloons to be marked with a warning that children under the age of eight cannot inflate the balloon without adult supervision.
The EU cited an American study which found that air balloons are the leading cause of death by suffocation in children.
A similar restriction already applies to children up to the age of 14 when using marketed fruit.
Curious thoughts can happen at home
It is also relatively absurd to have a directive which concerns European officials themselves - anyone in an official position in the EU cannot use the name Macedonia because of the sensitivity of the issue for Greece and must instead say FYROM (former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
The server Bankovnípoplatky.com, in cooperation with the Association of Liberal Economists Laissez Faire, nominated the EU Regulation on the size of food stocks on the territory of a member state, in addition to the previous absurdities.
The EU thus set the maximum volume of food stocks that could be on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic, for example, exceeded the volume of mushrooms in cans, for which we were threatened with a heavy fine.
The organisers of the survey were also impressed by the idea that certain countries should receive money for not having any sea, or by the idea of giving subsidies to applications for subsidies.
These ideas, of course, did not originate in Brussels but in Prague.
"We are at a disadvantage because we have no sea.
We will apply to the EU for reimbursement", declared the then Minister of Agriculture, Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD), in autumn 2004.
He argued that the cereal harvest had been very high and that the state stocks were overstocked as a result of the so-called intervention purchases.
Since the Czech Republic has another route to sea ports, Palas says the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
The European Commission finally went so far as to invite the Czech Republic to tender for the purchase of cereals from countries with no access to the sea.
The Ministry of Regional Development, headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), offered municipalities funding for grant applications, specifically for the establishment of grant applications in Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are the exception
Although regulations are easily the target of criticism in the Member States, some experts believe that the EU's efforts to regulate and thus to promote the effectiveness and development of the European Union as a whole deserve more credit.
A more serious problem, according to these experts, is the EU funding of projects which have nothing in common with the deepening of European integration, but which were forced upon us by individual Member States in the budget negotiations.
The Czech Republic is also experiencing a crisis of emotions in this country, as is the case in other EU countries, where the Czech Republic is fighting in Brussels for the right to use specific names of traditional products, and is not always winning the fight.
Although after a six-year struggle with Germany and Austria, the Czech Republic was able to defend the name 'Olomoucké tvarůžky' for domestic rum (Tuzemský rum), which has a tradition dating back to the 19th century, our producers had to change the name to 'Tuzemák'.
The term 'rum' may only be used for products made from sugar cane distillate, not for products made from sugar beet.
The official list of products registered in the EU now includes the world-famous Feta and Gorgonzola cheeses, the Lübeck Marzipan or Parma cheese, the Karlsbader Zwieback, the Pohořelice and Třeboň carp, and the Sauer Hopfen.
The Pardubice leaf cake or the Hořicer rolls can boast an EU trademark.
