The MVRDV architects prove that the real adventures are not only in the head - on the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built Bücherberg - 2 photos
"I think the building is funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there is something interesting to see", says Lisette Verhaig, a bystander on the side of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a nearby large company, says, "It's a nice house, though".
But I wonder why we need a library today.
They all have the Internet, iPads, e-books.
No one volunteers to go into one of those old-style libraries anymore, do they?
Spijkenisse, a sleepy town just outside the gates of Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The municipality of 80,000 inhabitants has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this absurd situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and to recreate the seven fictitious bridges on the euro banknotes as beautifully painted concrete-steel miniatures.
The success of the education campaign was limited.
And so the town fathers realized that there was only one way to master statistics: a library!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, master of the crazy-ass beam diagrams and producer of witty, often cynical, buildings, took the matter with his usual composure and appeared at the competition hearing in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the jury was still looking around in a daze and shaking their armpits, the cheeky Maas stacked his exquisite contribution of greatness into a pyramid and ended his actionist-based speech with the words, "Dear city!"
So this is it, my proposal for the book mountain of Spijkenisse, for the so-called book mountain!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain is uncovered.
It is part of a revitalization project which also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a few adjoining apartment and townhouses with a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This makes the faceless little town cake, which until now had nothing to offer but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a stunningly ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one might be tempted to think of a dairy factory, a piece of contemporary architecture.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to the Book
First impression: booked Eldorado under the cheese bells.
Although there is an elevator that runs through the middle of the mountain, the true joys of space and reading are found when the topography is climbed on foot.
The round glazed interior is bright and clear, the burnt-out clinker floor and the elegant street lamps speak unmistakably the language of a public town square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
Already, people are looking for a park bench, a dog, and boys and girls playing soccer.
And books, books, books everywhere.
"The bookshelves are usually located along the front, and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal", says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration upside down and built the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the Bücherberg is cleverly used: in the middle are offices, Internet library, chess club, environmental center and building technology center.
A special delight is the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall paneling, sometimes armor, sometimes stairwells.
The look, feel and smell are foreign.
Even the most experienced architects and civil engineers shake their heads at the thought of unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials", explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, at the request of the Standard.
And so one day in a farm in Friesland we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture.
For many years in the Netherlands, a thin plastic sheet of one millimetre has been used in greenhouses and in fields as a root support.
It's cheap and time-efficient.
The thin fabric lasts a season or two, then it's ready for the rubbish bin.
For the library, the fleece was pressed - for the first time in such quantities - into plates four centimeters thick.
Under heat and pressure, the so-called landbouwplastic (KLP) turns a dark, homogeneous, resilient material that smells like a new car and a sports shoe.
After 105 steps, you've reached the summit.
At the end of the nearly 500-meter-long trek, the Literature Café offers not only a fantastic view of the city but also Dutch croquettes and potted ficus trees.
They provide the atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literary mountains.
Donations for the new soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but this house is an example of ecological design, despite the many glass surfaces", says Trouborst.
It is heated and cooled by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain is covered with a glass roof, on sunny days the sun shines only briefly into the interior.
The wide wooden clay walls, which are set across the glass facade, serve as shade and absorb much of the sun's radiation.
The room climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done by fully automatic roller skates.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, was already venturing into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was there too.
And also TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who calls the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "long overdue soul".
The reason: At the opening a few weeks ago, each resident was invited to donate a book from his personal collection.
The aim is to fill the gaps in the library's 70,000 volumes, which are still not fully stocked.
The concept worked.
The shelves are filled to the brim.
"Nothing is worse than a half-empty library", says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that now, thanks to our invitation, "every resident has a certain relationship to this new house.
Everyone knows that their book is part of this building.
And if it's only for show.
In doing so, MVRDV has achieved the royal discipline that is known in the jargon as identity foundation.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
Young and uneducated as she may be.
This is a starting point for identity.
Szabo: 'Germans must play a greater role'
Germany abstained from voting on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic footing.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany initially signaled that it would vote against the request for observer status for the Palestinians at the United Nations.
But then Berlin refused.
Why is that?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think it supports the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the Libyan uprising in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
This was eventually enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yes, that's right.
The reason is that it is changing its foreign policy, away from a policy that was managed by the United States, so to speak, to a German foreign policy.
The European Union has a long history of developing a common foreign policy.
So the Germans are between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still trying to understand their role, but they are moving towards a more 'normal' foreign policy.
A foreign policy like they have in France or Britain.
What does a 'normal' foreign policy mean in German terms?
It shows a willingness to take positions on national interests which are independent of those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, that is, by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Did these economic interests influence the attitude towards the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
Firstly, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
So we must be careful not to offend the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
It definitely matters.
But I wouldn't want to put too much weight on it either, it's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German thinking.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining from voting on important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe and even in the United States there is a great deal of understanding for the German position.
That is why I do not think that this was a break as dramatic as the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect.
It is a signal that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
There are different opinions in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, has clearly voted to veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I think that the Obama administration has a pretty good understanding of the European position.
But due to the political situation here, the government cannot take this position publicly.
I think that the actual differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not that enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policies.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the USA on the one hand, and the position of the most important partners in the EU on the other hand?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would be a little easier for the Germans, of course, if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not the case at present.
So they can't be part of a broader line and instead have to push things from their own position.
That is what they are doing with the euro.
I believe that in future Germany will take a leading role in pushing Europe to a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, because of the relationship with Israel.
It's always been a sensitive subject.
But I think the Germans are aware that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as an important international player - does Germany even want to take on a leading role?
Or is Germany still finding it difficult to lead?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, every time Germany takes on a larger role, a variety of anti-German feelings are released.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
That's the old problem, you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this respect, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It has to be responsive to a variety of neighbors and opinions, and that's not easy.
The US is losing its influence in European politics, but the EU is not filling the vacuum. Who else is going to do it?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it's unpleasant for them and makes them much more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America collaborate on research on the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a fellow at the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Brand protection" in China: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani is a world-famous brand, and so is Ralph Polo Lauren.
But what is Armani Polo?
Behind this is a name which is officially registered in China but which has nothing to do with the companies of origin.
Yet, it is protected as long as the original owners of the name do not sue.
And even then, it's not clear that they're right.
"It is becoming more and more difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China", says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing who specializes in trademark infringement in the Far East.
Every week, a new case lands on my desk.
For the copycatters, a few extra letters are enough to register their marks.
So Gucci becomes just Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada, you have Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied in this way, such as the sportswear manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a folder with registrations from the Beijing Trademark Office.
On 14 September 2010, a Chinese company had the trademark Zegna DF Puma protected there, a name of art that also used the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
It is well known that the Chinese are the world champions in copying and infringing intellectual property.
In the big cities, there are multi-story department stores that sell almost exclusively counterfeits.
However, in the case of Mr Pattloch, on behalf of his clients, he has decided that Chinese companies will be granted the right to use a name which is already protected elsewhere by the Trademark Office.
The Chinese call it "Bang Mingpai", a brand of passenger side.
The word is "Bang Dakuan".
That's women who are attracted to rich men.
Chinese authorities are not aware of any guilt
"This is bad for business, and it must be fought", demands Pattloch.
"The brand is diluted, the exclusivity disappears, the damage to the image is enormous".
The financial losses and the legal costs of the industries affected run into the millions, especially in the case of expensive flagship products.
According to the market research company CLSA, China is the third largest market for luxury goods and the fastest growing, with a volume of EUR 15 billion per year.
However, deletions of dubious entries in the trade mark register are difficult to achieve and cost money.
The proceedings can drag on for up to nine years, with an uncertain outcome.
Pattloch reports cases in which the court dismissed claims because the name in question had become "market reality" after a long period of time.
If the plaintiff is unlucky, he would even have to pay the plagiarist for infringing his trademark in China, says Pattloch.
Sometimes the law of the jungle rules here.
