What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and gonorrhoea.
Common viral STIs include HIV, human papillomaviruses, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Fleas and ticks are parasitic STIs.
Who are the main groups affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea are mostly found in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of five of all reported cases of syphilis in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonas, candida, tripe and human papillomaviruses are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The prevalence of HIV among heterosexual adults in this country is comparatively low - yet, they account for around 20 percent of new HIV infections.
Chlamydia infections are much more common among adolescents than in other population groups.
