And then there's the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After extensive reading of research literature and presenting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom is defined as the experience of "wanting to do a satisfying activity but not being able to do it".
Boredom is different from apathy in that the person is not busy but wants to be.
Apathy, on the other hand, is the absence of the urge to act.
The key experience of boredom, he says, is a "disturbance of the attentional process coupled with a bad mood and a feeling that time is passing slowly".
Boredom can sound almost as depressing.
