We all get bored at one time or another - my delayed flight, a loudspeaker that's been ringing, a particularly tiresome movie.
But some people are more easily bored than others.
To measure these differences, researchers developed a "boring susceptibility scale" in the 1980s.
The scale includes statements such as "Many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
Using these scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to be bored than girls, says Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida - particularly when it comes to the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a pretty tight-knit bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he paged nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
