However, only 3 percent of parents said they felt bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he doesn't know if the percentages have gone up or down in terms of boredom.
But he is sure that "youth are perceived as particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers do not have much influence on their daily lives.
So, back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes it doesn't, because in extreme cases, it leads people to take extreme physical risks and resort to gambling or drugs to alleviate them, studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors have studied the relationship between boredom and creativity, including Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying the topic for more than two decades.
"Boring is the brain's way of telling you that you should be doing something else", says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn't always know what to do best at a given moment.
If you're bored and you use that energy to play guitar and cook, you'll be happy.
But while TV may provide feelings of happiness in the short run, these fade away in the long run.
So if you hand a bored child an iPad, it may help to relieve boredom, but it has not taught him to be entertained or to control himself, says Professor Fenske.
He adds: "Self-control is transferred from one situation to another".
The child not only learns to talk but also gains self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
We should not be too critical of them.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable outside the constant rush of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees with me.
"It sounds like we have to be bored more often, but boredom is the tormenting, unrelenting desire to do something meaningful", he says.
He thinks that people are really just looking for a way to shut down and relax.
