The world's most difficult job: the human work animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the bearers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur over the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others who work in literal hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by extracting sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the eastern part of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he has to descend each day to the bottom of his crater, where sulfur-containing gases from the ground solidify in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulphur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos, he carries them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the steep stone paths.
Although it is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2,386 meters, the exhausted climbers take more than 40 minutes to ascend at turtle-like speed, keeping their balance and pacing carefully so as not to slip and fall.
They know that every step can cost them their life, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the steep slopes of Kawah Ijen years ago.
The Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 euro cents for every kilo of sulfur they mine.
Once at the top, they make their way through the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and run with the tiringly heavy baskets three kilometres to the scales set up by a mining company a little further down at an altitude of 1850 metres
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been exploiting the volcano's resources since 1960 and (never mind) its workers, who are paid 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for each kilo of sulphur.
This is then sold to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees each, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life, and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"We normally carry 70 kg [60 lb] each way, so we get about 46,000 rupees [$2,500] each way", explains Anto, who normally does three trips a day.
It takes him three hours to complete each journey, but at the end of the day he has 138,000 rupees (£7.500) to his name.
What may seem like a miserable wage for such a sheerly inhuman effort is actually three times what he would earn from field work.
"The daily wage for the miners here, where the coffee harvest is 15,000 rupees (£1.50) a day and the average monthly income is two million rupees (£13) is very high", explains the bearer, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
He earned 75,000 rupees a day, and the work was not that hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village nearby, for a reason that is as important as sulfur in Indonesia: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindu, and I brought her to Java to convert her to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathing difficulties, frequent coughs and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases.
The 27-year-old Anto has been risking his life for three years at Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already left its first traces on him, although he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathing difficulties, frequent coughs and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he must pay for achieving his dream.
"I will work here for two more years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French", he promises in more than just plain English.
This young man, who is friendly and intelligent but has been punished by life, could work as a tourist guide, a waiter or a hotel receptionist, but instead he is doing the work of a porter.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other porters and gets up at two in the morning because the sulfur also flows out at night, where its characteristic yellow color glows blue in the dark.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought with his own money.
About 400 porters are loading baskets of sulfur on their shoulders at the bottom of the crater.
Despite its high profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulphur to save costs and does not supply any equipment to the operators, who work on their own account and are paid by weight.
They also do not get a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) per camera fee that the park's guards charge tourists for taking pictures of the volcano and the human remains, along with the 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) entrance fee.
"This work is for animals, not for people", protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old, stocky porter who has worked at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he will continue "as long as he can" because he needs the money to raise his three children between the ages of 10 and 18.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here, because the volcano was my whole life.
Even when the sulfur burns the throat and itches the eyes, when the wind suddenly turns and traps the miners in the thick pillars rising from the crater, the men are so tough that no one complains of serious illnesses ... of course, except for the usual breathing problems, arthritis, pain in the knees and blisters on the shoulders that have been deformed by the weight of the baskets.
With the basket on his back, Unainik, aged 53, is no longer able to carry 50kg.
Every day, he and his companions extract 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which is transported by three trucks over a goat track between the bushes to the camp at Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life", Unainik explains, opening his mouth wide, missing some teeth.
The eldest of his five children, now in his 30s, also works as a sulphur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty continues generation after generation in one of the world's toughest jobs: that of those who work as human burden on the Kawah Ijen.
