Offline private is offline private
The private sector
According to the dictionary, this is the private property or "that area of private life where one is entitled to protection from any interference".
What's private for someone under 16?
How does this definition apply to his daily life and to social networks?
Does he understand the dangers of sharing online situations that he would not share in real life?
El Periódico interviewed five teenagers between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequent users of the Internet.
In four cases, they linked the term to "something very personal" on a personal level and "to the password and the user" when applying it to social networks.
"I wouldn't reveal my deepest secrets in a post", says 10-year-old Jorge, trying to explain the meaning of "private" on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"These are very private secrets, my mother may know them, but not the whole world", he affirms.
I'll post some pretty pictures or pictures of games on FB.
I also spend time with people I know.
"I wouldn't share a photo that wasn't of me or someone who's making a fool of himself", he says.
The boy is aware that it is wrong to post obscene photos of nudity, crimes, or to write offensive or violent comments.
Jorge claims to know 35 friends on Facebook and 9 followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Including the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I joined Twitter to express myself and to write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if anyone will answer me, I just upload them", he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can quickly talk to distant relatives or friends", he says.
When asked, he replies that he would never accept an invitation from a stranger.
Even if someone recommended a stranger, he would ignore it.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space, and Ask, and in Ask, he admits not knowing 20 of the people he's added to his friends list.
"I'm not scared because we have something in common, like music", he says.
According to the boy, no one gave him any hints or asked for his address or telephone number.
"If someone harasses me or asks me to do it, I just remove them from my account", he admits.
José joined Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is not unfamiliar with the experience now known as cyberbullying.
A friend's acquaintance was blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who it was", he assures me.
According to José, the victim didn't close the user account.
"He was just doing it privately".
It then explains a series of steps to configure a user account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of people he knew in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, that's what I'd do if I didn't like him or if I wanted to punch him in the face.
"But I know that this is cyberbullying", he explains.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher with a university degree in education and learning, believes that in order to guide children and adolescents, it is necessary to understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet was born as a medium for finding information, but the emergence of these sites has changed the rules of the game", she says.
Porras explains that academic Marc Prensky, who holds a master's degree in education from Yale University and is the author of the book "Digital Natives and Immigrants", coined these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are those children and adolescents who grew up with this technology.
"We are the digital immigrants who are supposed to teach, when we are still learning", he says.
He explains that it is a complex issue "because we require them to have a defined criteria for what can be disseminated, published or said, and this at an age where the maturity is not sufficient for this".
"They should also be choosy if what matters most to them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends, without thinking of the consequences", he adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and adolescents about privacy is to ask them questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do it doesn't work", he says.
Porras then goes on to list some of the possibilities: There are some things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like to have a picture of you posted, like the one you posted about a friend?
Do you know what the others are posting about you?
Did you ask the other people's permission before you tagged photos of celebrations?
And one more question: Does everyone have to know what you're doing at any given moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they need to act online as they do offline.
It's the same rules.
"Anyone who is not online acts with respect, morality and other principles, and the same must be true for social networks", he explains.
Monitoring and surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, elementary school teacher, and educational consultant, comments that it is essential that parents read the social network policies carefully.
Understanding all the paragraphs will give you a solid foundation for discussing with your children the importance of having a Web-based account.
"For example, age, or what you can share or publish", he explains.
According to Guardia, the children need to be reminded of the lesson "You must not talk to strangers".
The conclusion of the Unasur summit without the publication of the Lima Declaration
The sixth summit of the presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima declaration, which had been announced earlier and which was supposed to be signed by the seven governments present.
Efe repeatedly tried to obtain access to the document signed at the VI Ordinary Session of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but sources in the State and Presidential Chancellery initially said that they would hand it over after the closure, but then stated that it would be published on the website of the Peruvian government at some point.
When asked about the text, they said that the contents were explained by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
The access of journalists to information about the summit was restricted at all times.
During the day, the only image of the President's meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the message "private meeting, limited audio".
The few pieces of information that circulated among journalists were obtained by the spokesmen of some of the governments of Unasur present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document circulated during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused unease among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media outlets who demanded more information.
After that, the Peruvian presidency sent an email to the media with the summit's "concluding statement", but it was Humala's statement and not the official document concluding the summit.
The third summit of the Arab States of South America (ASPA) was held in Peru last October, and on this occasion too, despite press calls, the so-called Lima declaration, which had been announced earlier, was not published.
The official ASPA website confirms that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems were available to journalists, but they severely restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to accept a ruling by the Hague Court of Justice that settles a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the ICC, which begins in The Hague on Monday, in the trial initiated by Lima v. Santiago, to hear the pleas of both sides.
"We will follow and implement the judgment on the differences that we are presently submitting to this international court", Humala said along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will continue to be a country that adheres to international laws, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, makes agreements and submits to international courts", Piñera added, saluting Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by both Presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia, following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua that it considered a grave error, had brought an action against the Bogotá Agreement, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this international court.
The summit was attended by the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from Unasur since 2011 following the ousting of its president, Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host, President Ollanta Humala, opened the talks in the morning and concluded the summit shortly after lunch in Lima.
The President read out the final document, in which he announced that 16 decisions had been taken and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries had been defined, with a total investment of $17 billion.
The EU's newly elected president, Mr Ban Ki-moon, said that the EU was "a step forward in the process of achieving the goal of South American citizenship, and we are extending the decisions on residence rights".
He said that measures were being taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organised transnational crime, to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America, and to act together and efficiently in the event of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not be a triumph, but a means to increase our production capacity and to show our peoples a better future", added Humala.
"We have decided to prioritize a series of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the spatial connections in South America and especially in rural and border areas...thereby uniting our countries and opening up new economic forms", the Peruvian president said in a statement read out.
The Commission has also proposed that the European Parliament should be consulted on the draft directive on the protection of the environment and the protection of the environment against pollution from industrial sources.
The final document also dealt with the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve its re-admission to the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region of prosperity and peace, with good neighbourly relations, was another aspect emphasised at the Summit.
In this context, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before he began his participation in the regional meeting that he expected to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, in Mexico on Saturday, in order to deal respectfully with the maritime conflict following a ruling by the ICJ that was challenged by Bogotá.
"I may meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)", said Santos.
'We will examine all these ways - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also makes talks with Nicaragua necessary,' he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will handle this matter as civilized and respectful as possible", added Santos.
Santos and Ortega are to meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the inauguration of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
The EU's defence ministers met in advance of the summit to adopt the 2013 Action Plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter is currently excluded.
Peru will hold the rotating presidency of the regional bloc.
'South America must learn from the integration of its citizens', says Rafael Correa
Ecuador's President Rafael Correa today confirmed that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal, with "South America actually having something to learn from Europe".
Correa, who attended the 6th Summit of Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) in Lima, told Peru's state television that Europeans "killed each other in the Second World War and other conflicts" and "today they are practically a fatherland".
In this sense, he defended the project of creating a South American citizenship that would promote the member states of Unasur.
"Free movement of citizens and workers must be achieved in all South American countries, as is already the case in the Andean Community; however, there are still reactionary sectors that seek a return to the past", he warned.
The Ecuadorian President also supported the reorganization of the Organization of American States (OAS) with the aim of reducing the influence of the Anglo-Saxon states and taking account of those who signed the San José Convention on Human Rights.
Those who teach never commit themselves to anything, and in return we South Americans always sign everything.
"It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is based in Washington and is financed by the United States", he said, referring to Ecuador's granting political asylum to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
Correa assured that he did not regret the decision because he did not betray his principles, but followed his "deep democratic values and views on human rights".
He added that at the time there was "well-founded suspicion that Assange would be extradited to a third country and his case would not be respected".
He also criticised the Swedish judiciary, which had asked him to be interrogated on his own territory for an alleged sexual offence, whereas "Swedish law allows this by means of a videoconference, which could have been carried out through the Ecuadorian embassy in London".
Correa stated that there was a danger that Assange's health and mental state would be compromised.
"I have not spoken to him since he arrived at our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he has a small problem with his lungs, but it is not serious", said the Ecuadorian head of state.
However, there is a risk of physical and psychological harm because he is confined in a confined space and cannot exercise outdoors.
"This would affect the health of every person", he added.
Correa said that the solution to the asylum granted to Assange since June in the Ecuadorian embassy in London was to grant him a free letter to travel to Ecuador, and that this was in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the legal authorities of Europe.
We are not dealing with human rights, we are not using that word in this case, but there have been constant talks.
"The solution to this problem is in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the legal authorities of Europe because Assange's lawyer Baltazar Garzón is conducting a series of proceedings in various European bodies", he explained.
And if Britain grants this discharge tomorrow, I think that's done.
And if Sweden interrogated Mr Assange in the Ecuadorian embassy in London or via Skype, as Swedish law allows and as has been done in other cases, the problem would be solved.
Correa used the occasion to assert himself as a defender of press freedom, saying that what he does not tolerate is "the mediocrity, the malice and the lies that undermine free speech".
"The greatest enemies of press freedom are not the evil and perverse politicians, but bad journalists who seek profit and blackmail", he said.
In this sense, he congratulated himself that Ecuador would no longer be ruled by such journalists "nor by the bankers or hegemonic and bourgeois countries", and anticipated that if reelected, he would "deepen the revolution to continue in this right direction".
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto against Paraguay in the Unasur at least until its next elections, arguing that the body "must remain tough and not allow any opportunism and no coup d'état disguised as legal" because it "destroyed the legitimacy of democracy in Paraguay".
The Ecuadorian President also considered his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, 'absolutely justified' in his desire to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime boundaries between the two countries, now and after the ruling of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which favoured the maritime sovereignty of Nicaragua.
At present, this judgment is not being implemented.
It is a problem between a South American state and a Central American state.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome in the pursuit of a common path.
They need to be treated comprehensively so that they can be overcome and looked at in the future.
He also hoped for a successful resolution of the maritime boundary disputes between Peru and Chile before the same court, and said that "it is right for Latin America to call international bodies if both countries commit to accept the judgment, even if it is very harsh".
Regarding the possibility of running for the next presidential elections in Ecuador to achieve his third consecutive term, he stated that he sees this possibility "with a lot of optimism and joy, although it is sometimes very difficult".
Correa assured that if he lost the February 2013 elections, he would retire from political life.
I have never been interested in power, but in conditions of such injustice as Ecuador, this socioeconomic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
"My political movement believed that I was the one who guaranteed this probable victory, so I have to live up to that responsibility", he said.
If I win, it will be my last term as president, after which I will retire from public life.
This is true even if we lose.
"It is decided", he explained.
Correa also referred to the treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez's health problems in Cuba.
I just spoke to the Vice President of Venezuela, Nicolás Maduro, and he told me that he had gone there for a scheduled, routine treatment and that he was expected to be able to travel back to Cuba after the election campaign.
"It does not in any way mean a decline in President Chávez's health", he commented.
The Ecuadorian President took part in the 6th Summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) in Lima today, which ended with a call for greater regional integration to ensure sustainable progress, equality and security.
AIDS is now a cause of death that is too late to be recognized
Fabrizio was 21 years old when his test result was confirmed as HIV positive.
"It was like a bomb went off", he says of the moment he received the diagnosis, which the doctor tried to "deaden" without apparent success.
He kept it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness himself and began to learn about it, and he did so with such dedication that he was just celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), which he joined after several struggles in 1994.
Fabrizio has lived with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was hard to imagine in the early 1990s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigmas.
Even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying good-bye "because it was a dead end".
Back then, AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome with a good quality of life.
However, many people who are still coming to the clinic are unaware of their illness and have already been damaged by the virus and have exhausted their immune systems, and are victims of opportunistic infections.
Thirty-one years after AIDS first appeared in the world, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient who starts treatment in time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same", said the head of the HCG's HIV Unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, adding that this information was backed up by a respected scientific publication in April of this year.
The specialist in infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS, Andrade Villanueva, commented that scientists since 2008 concluded that while AIDS is not a death sentence, that the years of survival and the quality of life depend on the degree of the immune system impairment of the people at the beginning of the treatment, and that those who are not drug dependent have the greatest chances: up to 30 years with a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years with a count of 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above means that in this sense, a 25-year-old who is diagnosed as HIV-positive "can easily live to 75 years of age, as long as he is under control", said the expert.
To put this progress in perspective, it is important to remember that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Even though mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNUNAIDS Annual Report), it is still true that since the emergence of AIDS, 60 percent of the patients in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011 and 187 people died in May this year, but the state has been assured that universal access to antiretroviral drugs has been available since 2005.
- So why do people still die from it?
- In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and this is our hospital.
The problem is that people come in at a very advanced stage because they don't know their infection status, which is very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us with a concomitant infection, and to influence the global mortality rate, earlier diagnosis is needed, so that all those who need it are offered a massive range of screening tests".
This proposal is supported by the experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) and by patients like Fabrizio, who had his test done in a private laboratory, and only because it was done by a friend of his who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS stage and even had Kaposi sarcoma (a cancerous tumor), which is one of the common complications.
It's different when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die, and they don't want to hear it.
"If I'm going to die, I'd rather explode three times", they say in my case.
The change was for the better, I eat well, I exercise and I take the medication.
Today, his parents only know that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, like everyone else.
"I work, I do a lot, I have an active but responsible sex life, I take care of my health and that of the other person", says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO to encourage those who are afraid today, on World AIDS Day.
They should get tested if they are at risk, and the sooner they know if they are HIV positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like everyone else.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter.
There are big gaps between the health programs and the average citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has taken up the cause of HIV.
And the most important thing is prevention.
At the designated sites, "the distribution of condoms has actually increased; they used to give them out individually, now they give us packages of a hundred, which is fine, but there are still people who don't have access to a condom", he said.
Young people are at risk of new infections.
"What do you need it for?" is a common question of derision from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy and health-care workers, who do not want young people to be exposed, the correspondent assured.
He suggested that this inefficient distribution be reoriented, with condoms not only being placed behind the counter but also in dispensers in public toilets in facilities frequented by young people.
It is not to promote promiscuity.
They are not to be paid for beer and motel, as Governor Emilio Gonzalez replied to the question whether condoms would be distributed under his administration.
"Sexuality is not like that; the best thing to do is to bring the condoms closer to those who are already engaged in sexual activity", he said.
Key data from Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 of which are AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state ranks fourth nationally in new and cumulative AIDS cases, and 13th in HIV.
92% of cases are sexually transmitted, 6% are bloodborne and 2% are perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people are living with HIV, because for every registered case, there are four or five people who don't know it.
The United States Court of Appeals upheld a judgment not recognising the restructuring of the liabilities of the Vitro Group, which was reached through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico, and this sets an ominous precedent for any national company with a subsidiary in a neighbouring country that has payment problems.
So, it could be said that the procedures for the survival of companies that Mexican laws allow are not valid in the Land of the Stars and Stripes, contrary to international agreements.
In practice, the June 15 recognition of the ruling by Judge Harlin Hale of the Bancarrotas District Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican companies helplessly exposed to the confiscation of their property across the Rio Bravo.
However, the decision opens the door to the largest glass manufacturer in Mexico to appeal to the United States Supreme Court on three grounds of inconsistency.
While the judge in the main proceedings points out that the creditors must be subject to the bankruptcy law of the United States, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, with its seat in New Orleans, first of all states that the case in the main proceedings is that of the commercial bankruptcy dealt with in Mexico.
The first point would mean that international cooperation in insolvency proceedings of companies with a transnational profile is not known.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Trade Law was created for this purpose, with the American Law Institute acting as arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment states that, without the votes of the companies after the recognition of the liabilities in the bankruptcy estate that the Vitro branches had with their parent company, the necessary majority for the restructuring of the liabilities would not have been achieved.
However, this possibility is recognized by Mexican law.
In fact, Vitro is not the first case where this scheme has been approved.
There are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose liabilities to group companies have been confirmed by the Instituto Federal de Concursos Mercantiles (Federal Institute of Commercial Competitions).
It is also true that, after deducting the votes of the branches, the creditors of Vitro, the creditors who brought legal proceedings against Vitro in the United States courts, i.e. the VCFs such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, did not obtain a majority.
The vote would have been 45 percent to 37 percent.
This is not taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, Vitro is to blame for its difficult situation since 2008 in the context of the great economic crisis in the United States, which hit the country.
For this reason, the González Sada family opposes the decision of the Court of Appeal, which is the same court, so that the vote is taken by the full court, that is, by all the judges, because only three of them voted.
If this is not done, the Cerciorare challenge is filed, which requires the review of the case by a higher authority, in this case the Supreme Court of the United States.
The gravity of this case is that the Court left out a document sent by the Mexican Government under the Figura Amicus curiae (Friend of the Court) describing the proceedings conducted by Vitro under the Commercial Competitions Act, and which points out that it had strictly adhered to the agreements signed by both countries to comply with Chapter 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Code.
It is also noted that the country has subscribed to the principles of the United Nations International Trade Commission, i.e. the established rules for cases of cross-border insolvency, which guarantee the equality of debtors and creditors.
