Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
The world-famous basketball player, Héctor "Hetin" Reyes, has been involved in the sport for more than 60 years and has traveled the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as much of a mental collection of the history of the country's basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being confined to a wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes was part of the sport for 6 years, whether as a lower class player, player of the first national league, official and director in the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or president of the Basketball Association.
"I've put on many hats in basketball throughout my life, even several at the same time, when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the national team and president of the federation in the 90s", Reyes recalled during a visit by Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he lives with Isabel, his faithful wife of more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life".
Reyes is not exaggerating.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career and bear witness to them.
Bayamón in the heart
The most emotional memories are those of his time with the Vaqueros from the mid-1950s as a player to 1982, when he celebrated his 15th anniversary as co-manager or general manager of the club.
"Those were my best years, the ones I enjoyed the most, because I was able to be part of eight championships of the Vaqueros since 1967 whether as manager, co-manager or coach.
There were many rewarding years, including five consecutive championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to a championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy made his debut on BSN.
From then on, Cuco Ortiz took over, and he was a very good administrator", says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who worked here as a coach and was employed at the University of Alabama at Birmingham, telling me, "I have a very strong player, six feet tall.
Do you want it?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended free-throw specialist Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and was one of our best pitchers.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had made it possible for Bayamon to win a championship, Gausse would have made it possible for him to win another.
The Vaqueros' championship with Gausse was awarded to him, but from a distance, because he was already at the top of the association in 1988.
At the time, he preferred to enjoy his and Mincy's executions on the national team.
I remember the first time we won against the United States in the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico.
The European Parliament has also been asked to take a decision on the proposal for a directive on the protection of workers from the risks of exposure to asbestos at work.
Was that 1990 World Cup group the best national team you've ever seen?
She's one of the best, like the one who beat the Dream Team in the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite is the team from the Pan American Games in 1991 in Cuba, where we won gold and gave the U.S. team a fight, like when they won bronze against us in the World Championships.
