And he's not the only professor who's teaching classes on the end of the world this semester, which was supposed to be the last in history.
At Temple, visiting professor Barry Vacker is teaching a course on "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Each week, students examine apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We analyze why these ideas spread over time", he said, as well as the ways in which hypothetical scenarios are offered that lead to a particular human behavior.
For example, if nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, war could break out.
This month, the students analyzed apocalyptic movies and how they compared to real life.
"I tried to inform the students about what is possible, probable, plausible and impossible", said Vacker.
